  "prompt": "Did any ancient civilization not use slaves?",
  "response": "While slavery was widespread in many ancient civilizations, there were some societies that either had limited slavery or practiced different forms of servitude:\n\n1. Minoan Civilization (Crete)\n\u2022 Archaeological evidence suggests minimal or no traditional slavery\n\u2022 More egalitarian social structure\n\n2. Some Native American Societies\n\u2022 Certain tribes practiced captive-taking but not lifelong, hereditary slavery\n\u2022 Captives could often be adopted or integrated into the community\n\n3. Early Buddhist Societies\n\u2022 Buddhist teachings discouraged slavery\n\u2022 Some Buddhist kingdoms had less institutionalized slavery\n\n4. Some Polynesian Societies\n\u2022 Practiced forms of servitude different from chattel slavery\n\u2022 Social hierarchies existed but not always based on ownership of people\n\nHowever, it's important to note that completely slavery-free societies were extremely rare. Most ancient civilizations had some form of forced labor or servitude, even if it differed from the chattel slavery familiar from more recent historical periods.\n\nEven societies that were relatively progressive for their time, like ancient Athens or the Roman Republic, heavily relied on slave labor. True absence of slavery was extremely uncommon in pre-modern societies.\n\nHistorians continue to research and debate the nuances of labor systems in ancient civilizations.",
